1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. e4 d6 5. Nge2 {This line is known as Kramer's
Variation though the Hungarian GM Szabo did work this line.} 5... O-O 6. Ng3 c5
{I had lost a previous game to John where I had played the Averbakh variation
(5.Be2, 6.Bg5). This move was expected.} 7. d5 e6 8. Be2 exd5 9. exd5 {
cxd5 by White gives the position a Benoni type pawn structure.} 9... Re8 10.
O-O Nbd7 11. Bf4 {
The major alternative is f4 which can allow Black to sacrifice a pawn.} (11. f4
a6 12. f5 b5 13. fxg6 hxg6 14. cxb5 Qb6 15. Kh1 axb5 16. Bxb5 Ba6 17. Bxa6 Qxa6
18. Bf4 Ne5 19. Rb1 Rab8 20. Qd2 Rb4 {
As in Rembinger - Pendersen, Gausdal 1991.}) 11... Ne5 12. Qd2 Bd7 {
Now I'm out of the theory available to me.} 13. Bg5 Qb6 {This move for Black
is wrong as I felt that the Queen is better placed on a5 and on b6 it hampers
any Queenside counterplay with b5.} 14. f4 Neg4 15. f5 {
Necessary to try and deny the e3 square for Black.} 15... Rf8 $2 {
h6 is necessary for Black here now or on the next move.} 16. h3 Ne5 17. Bxf6
Bxf6 18. Nce4 Bh8 $4 {Where does this Bishop go? There is no active square for
it. I feel it cannot go to h4 as White plays Qh6.} 19. f6 Rfd8 20. b3 Bc8 {
This is necessary to allow the Black Knight access to f8 via d7.} 21. Qh6 Nd7
22. Ng5 Nf8 23. Bd3 Bd7 24. Nxf7 {If Black takes the Knight, White sacrifices
the Bishop with Bxg6+, If Black takes with the pawn the Bishop on h8 falls or
if Black takes with the Knight Qxh7+ kf8 Qxg6 is winning clearly fot White.}
1-0

