{I am giving this game first as it was my only loss in the tournament. My
opponent played the Steinitz Defence to my Ruy Lopez. As it has a rather
passive reputation, I was immediately siezed with an insane confidence that I
was destined to win this game. It doesn't pay to be too cocky!!} 1. e4 e5 2.
Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. d4 Bd7 5. d5 {At this point I got the idea referred to in
my introductory remarks that my opponent was going to play a cautious and
defensive game. This made me feel pretty good, as I said.} 5... Nce7 6. Qe2 a6
7. Bxd7+ Qxd7 8. c4 c5 {Either locking the centre for the moment or giving
herself the choice (after dxc6) of a central break with d5 at some point.} 9.
O-O g6 10. Bd2 a5 11. Nc3 h6 12. Qd1 Nc8 {The start of some complicated (To
me!) and patient manoevring. The Knight has access to better squares from d7
than from a7.} 13. Qa4 {
I don't know why an exchange of Queens seemed good at this point.} 13... Nb6
14. Qxd7+ Nxd7 15. b3 Be7 {Unexpected after preparing to fianchetto on g7.
Still the Bishop can support K-side pawn advances better from e7.} 16. Rfb1 b6
17. Ne1 Ngf6 18. f3 {
Establishing a very aesthetic looking pawn chain din't you think?} 18... g5 19.
Nc2 Nf8 20. a3 {Preparing to push b4 andd try to seize an open file.} 20... Ng6
{She's not worried by the prospect of b4.} 21. b4 a4 22. bxc5 bxc5 23. Rb7 O-O
24. Rab1 g4 $2 {Losing the h pawn.} 25. Bxh6 {I have won a pawn, am attacking
her Rook and have doubled my own Rooks. I'm feeling pretty good about now!}
25... Rfd8 26. R1b6 {
The start of an attempt to double Rooks on the seventh rank.} 26... Nd7 27. Rc6
gxf3 28. gxf3 Kh7 29. Bd2 {
Thinking there might be a use for the Bishop on the e1 - a5 diagonal.} 29...
Kg7 30. Rcc7 Nf6 31. Ne3 Ng8 {Defending the Bishop again.} 32. Nf5+ Kf6 {
Now the Bishop is adequately defended.} 33. Nxe7 N8xe7 34. Rd7 {
Hoping for a Rook exchange and the win of the d pawn.} 34... Rxd7 35. Rxd7 Ra6
36. Nb5 Nc8 {Defending the d pawn.} 37. Nc7 Nf8 38. Nxa6 Nxd7 {
Getting rid of the annoying Rook.} 39. Nc7 Ndb6 {Attacking the c pawn.} 40. Nb5
Ke7 41. Kg2 {Now I start trying to Queen the h pawn hoping the Knight will
keep the King tied to the d pawn and the Black Knights won't get across in
time. The Bishop might be able to help too.} 41... Nxc4 {
Now material is level and Black has  a passed pawn of her own.} 42. Bc1 Na5 43.
Kg3 Nb3 44. Be3 Nd4 45. Nxd4 exd4 {The Knight exchange was a very good idea.
Black now has two connected passed pawns against my one.} 46. Bd2 Nb6 47. Kf2
c4 {The pawn roller rolls!} 48. Ke2 {
The only chance now is to try to exchange the Bishop for the two passed pawns.}
48... Nd7 49. Bc1 Nc5 50. Bf4 Nd3 51. Bd2 Nb2 52. h4 c3 {If Bxc3 The King
can't approach to get the second pawn and will be tied down to guarding it
from Queening. This will leave the h pawn at the Black King's mercy.} 53. f4 f6
54. h5 cxd2 55. Kxd2 Nc4+ {Forking King and pawn.} 56. Kd3 Nxa3 57. Kxd4 Nb5+
58. Kc4 a3 {If 59.Kb3 a2 60.Kxa2 Nc3 and the pawns fall.} 0-1

