the pawn on e5, hoping that White will feel oblidged to open the kingside up
with f4 & untimately g3.} 25. Rfd1 Nc6 26. f4 Qe3 27. g3 Qf3+ 28. Kg1 Nd4 29.
Bf1 $6 {29.Bxb5 was much better.} 29... Qxd1 30. Rxd1 Nf3+ 31. Kf2 Rxd1 32.
Kxf3 {Otherwise I was threatening the Rook fork from d2.} 32... Rxf1+ 33. Kg2
Rd1 34. Kh3 {Apparent safety for the White King.} 34... Kf7 {
Because White was now threatening 35.Qb3.} 35. Qe2 Rcd8 36. Qb2 R8d2 37. Qa3 h5
$5 {Instead of defending my queenside pawns, I decided to create mating
threats to White's "safe" King.} 38. Qf3 Ra1 39. Qe4 Raxa2 40. Kh4 {Otherwise 4
0...Rxh2 is +mate! But now if I play 40...Rxh2, White plays 41.Kg5 and the
position now looks extremely promising for White, so...} 40... Re2 $1 41. Qd3
Rad2 $1 42. Qb1 Rxh2+ 43. Kg5 Rc2 $1 {
