45.gxh4?? Rcg2 and very soon White gets mated!} 45... h3 {
Now it's an advanced passed pawn with a strong threat of promotion.} 46. f5 {
White's last card, he opens up the position around the Black King in order to
be able to do some damage with his Queen, winning a few pawns, hoping for a
blunder with a route to mate or failing that a perpetual check.} 46... gxf5 47.
gxf5 exf5 48. Qb3+ e6 49. Qe3 Rhd2 {I considered c2 & d2 the best squares for
my 2 Rooks, preventing the White Queen from having access to the c-file and
planning to block a future check with my d2 Rook.} 50. Qg5 {
Of course not 50.Qxh3??...Rh2 and it's a simple win for Black.} 50... h2 51.
Qf6+ Ke8 52. Qxe6+ Kd8 53. Qb6+ Kd7 54. e6+ Ke7 55. Qb7+ Kxe6 56. Qxa6+ Rd6 57.
Qa1 b4 58. Qb1 Rg2 59. Kh5 $4 {A blunder in a lost position.} 59... Rd8 60.
Qe1+ Kf7 {It's mate in 3. White cannot prevent both ...Rh8+ and h1=R+. He can
only stop one of those moves from mating (if for example he plays 61.Qa1)
thereafter the other move will give mate. 61.Qg3 Rxg3 62.Kh4 Rdg8 63.Kh5 and I
have a choice between  h1=R+mate and Rh3+mate and Rh8+mate. Alternatively he
could play 61.Qe6 7 or 8 check, but this only prolongs the game for one more
move and it's still mate on the next move, hence Graham's resignation.} 0-1

