White has to retreat otherwise the Queen is lost after 13...Na5.} 13... Nd4 ({
In Ost-Hansen-Nunn (1974), Black played} 13... Bh6 14. Qg4 $2 e4 $1 15. Bxf4
exd3+ 16. Kf1 {Black has a winning attack, proving that in this variation, one
tempo lost can be disastrous. 14.Bd5 would be better.}) 14. Qg4 Bh6 {14...Bg7!?
is Ekebjaerg-Timmerman, corr. 1991 which Black won after extraordinary
complications.} 15. Bd2 Bxa8 16. O-O-O Nxb3+ 17. axb3 Ne8 {The position after
17.axb3 has been reached a few times before, but 17...e4 looks better here.
The Knight retreat allows White to complete his development.} 18. Nf3 Nf6 19.
Qh3 d6 (19... d5 20. Rhe1 e4 21. dxe4 dxe4 22. Bxf4+ Ke8 23. Bxh6) 20. Rhe1 Re8
21. d4 e4 {Black does play e4 but it is less effective now.} 22. Kb1 e3 23.
fxe3 fxe3 24. Ng5 {Blocks the Bishop and threatens to take the e-pawn.} 24...
Nd5 25. Qg3 Bxg5 26. hxg5 e2 27. Rc1 Nc7 28. Ka2 Nb5 {White maintains a
material advantage, but Black has a pesky passed pawn on the seventh rank, a
powerful Bishop, and is attacking the d-pawn. White now tries to deal with the
Bishop whilst protecting the pawn at the same time.} 29. d5 Nd4 (29... Bxd5 30.
c4) 30. Bc3 Nf5 31. Qf4 Qe4 32. Bf6+ Kc8 33. Qxe4 Rxe4 34. c4 {The position
has clarified. White plans to play to win the e-pawn oe exploit Black's
backward h-pawn.} 34... Kb8 $1 {I was baffled by this mysterious move at the
time, but it became clear soon enough!} 35. Rc3 $2 (35. Rc2 Ng3 36. Rc3 Rg4 (
36... Nf5 37. Rh3) 37. Re3) 35... Ne3 $1 36. Rxe3 {If 36.Rxe2 Nxd5! and now it
is no longer check if the Knight is recaptured by the c-pawn, the point of 34..
.Kb8. The Knight now has to be captured or the g-pawn will fall and the e-pawn
can queen.} 36... Rxe3 37. Kb1 b5 38. Kc2 Bb7 39. Bd4 Re7 40. Bg1 Kc8 41. Kd3
Ba6 42. Bh2 Rc7 43. Bxd6 bxc4+ 44. Kd4 Rd7 45. bxc4 $1 {Even after the Bishop
sacrifice, White still has very good drawing chances, but this is the only way
to continue playing for a win.} 45... Rxd6 46. Rxe2 Kd8 47. b4 {
White has connected passed pawns for the Bishop and an active Rook.} 47... Bb7
48. Re4 Rd7 49. Rf4 Ke7 50. Rf6 Ke8 51. g3 {
Removes the pawn from a white square and prevents a check at f4.} 51... Re7 52.
c5 Bc8 53. Rf4 Rb7 {Re1 may be better, to get behind the pawns.} 54. Kc4 Re7
55. c6 Re3 56. Rh4 Ke7 {
Black sacrifices two pawns in order to activate the King.} ({The alternative} 
56... Re7 57. d6 Rf7 58. Re4+ Kf8 {or d8} 59. Re5 {
leaves Black with little space, and White with passed pawns on the sixth rank.}
) 57. Rxh7+ Kd6 58. Rxa7 Re4+ 59. Kb5 Rg4 (59... Kxd5 60. Rd7+ $1 Ke6 (60...
Bxd7 61. cxd7) (60... Ke5 61. Re7+ Kd5 62. Rxe4 Kxe4 63. Kb6 Kd5 64. Kc7 Bf5
65. b5 {wins.}) 61. Rd8 {wins the Bishop.}) 60. Ra8 Bf5 61. Rd8+ Kc7 62. Rf8
Rxg5 63. Rf7+ Kd6 64. Kb6 Rg4 65. b5 Rxg3 66. Rf8 Kxd5 67. c7 Rc3 68. Kb7 Bd7
69. Rd8 Ke6 70. b6 Ke7 {Black offered a draw around here, and again a few
moves later. I thought that it wasn't heading for a draw.....} 71. c8=Q Bxc8+
72. Rxc8 Rg3 73. Rc5 Kd7 {To prevent Kc7.} 74. Rg5 $4 {Wins the g-pawn,
followed by the Rook wending its way to a5 either directly or via g8 and a8 if
Black plays Ra3 .......EXCEPT that Black's Rook is at g3 not b3, which is
where I was convinced it was, even though Rg3 was plainly written on the
scoresheet. White should have played 74.Ra5 threatening Ka8 quening the pawn,
and if 74...Rb3, 75.Rg5 and the plan is as above. Either way White is winning.
  I don't think there is a book entitled Zen and the Art of Playing Chess (if
not maybe there should be), but the end of this game is a veryzen moment.
White has just achieved a winning position for the second time in the game
after much effort (and after turning down two draw offers) and finally loses
after a bizarre clerical mistake. There must be better ways of spending my
time..........} 0-1

