{My first foray into the world of email international chess began in the
Spring of 1999. Most games needed only 3 or 4 months to complete. The one that
I have chosen for annotating took a bit longer, as my Brazilian opponent had
to sell his own computer and arrange to forward the email from a borrowed
machine! In the end I managed 4 wins 1 loss and 1 draw in the tournament.} 1.
Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. d4 Bg7 5. Bg5 Ne4 6. Bf4 {So much for theory, as
far as my limited resources go. Though our wise database checkers may be able
to point out precedents..} 6... Nxc3 7. bxc3 e6 {I'm not sure whether this is
the right time for Black to play this, limiting the c8 Bishop.} 8. e3 O-O 9.
Bd3 b6 {
A less quiet possibility here would be 9 ... c5 or 9 ... dxc4 followed by c5}
10. cxd5 {I had decided Black would not want 10 ... Qxd5 11 Bxc7 but after 11 .
.. Qc6 he does OK. My main intention was to have a position with d5 blocked,
thus making a queen side fianchetto unattractive.} 10... exd5 {Black goes for
the pawn capture anyway. After all, the c8 h3 diagonal is available again.} 11.
O-O Bg4 12. h3 Be6 {The Bishop is driven back but it may still be a
sacrificial force to be reckoned with  if  there is a build up against h3.} 13.
Ne5 {A probing move, eyeing c6.} 13... f6 {A response that looks weakening} 14.
Ng4 g5 {An aggressive use of pawns in front of the King to keep me from
achieving results on the h6 square. It is surprising how well Black does with
this.} 15. Bg3 Nc6 16. Nh2 {This was prompted by the attractive opening of the
d1 h5 diagonal in an attempt to combine Bishop and Queen against h7.} 16... Ne7
{Bringing more defensive forces into the arena.} 17. Qc2 {The Qh5 line just
does not seem to break through. Black has enough defenders to ward off the
threats.} 17... h5 {Another pawn in front of the king! No battening down of
hatches here. I decided to respond with a pawn thrust of my own, to give my g3
Bishop somewhere to retreat and to break things up a bit.} 18. f4 h4 19. Be1
Qd7 {Now Black is building threats himself.  A well timed sac on h3 with
advanced pawns to follow.} 20. fxg5 fxg5 21. Rxf8+ Rxf8 22. Qe2 {
A bit of attack and defence. The Queen covers g4 and h5.} 22... c5 {A sudden sw
itch to the queen side which does not seem to be in keeping with all the
activity on the other wing.} 23. Nf3 c4 24. Bc2 Bf6 25. e4 g4 26. Nxh4 gxh3 {
The Knight looks a little odd on the edge but it has avoided being pinned and
the following pawn push provokes a piece exchange which may well be the
turning point.} 27. e5  27... Bxh4 28. Bxh4 Bg4 {
Harassing the Queen may not be the best here. Perhaps Bf5 instead.} 29. Qd2 Rf7
{Again Black's choice looks doubtful. The Rook may have some defensive role
and perhaps even have an attacking square on g7 but ..} 30. Bf6 Kf8 {
Trying to run before the Queen drops in.} 31. Qh6+ Ke8 32. Bxe7 {This took a
while to decide as I had kept thinking I needed to keep both Bishops. But no,
this wins material.} 32... Qxe7 {And not with the Rook, as then 33. Qh8+  Kf7 
34. Rf1+. And not with the King as 33. Bg6 Rf8 34. Qg7 or Qh4+} 33. Bg6 hxg2
34. Kxg2 Bf3+ {Bf5 may have made White work harder, forcing White to win the
exchange before his Rook can take up an active role.} 35. Kh2 Be2 {
Again, Black might prolong matters with Be4	} 36. Rg1 Bd3 {
Too late, and my opponent later admitted he had thought I'd played Kg1 here!}
37. Bxf7+ Qxf7 {Finally the Rook, pinned since move 33, is removed.} 38. Qh8+ {
In view of 38...Qf8 39. Rg8 or 38. Ke7 Rg7} *

