{Queen's Indian.  Playing Bernard is something that every c.c. player should
experience, its a riot of fun from start to finish. For me our game faded into
a secondary role and thats how it should be, making c.c. a very special tool
and Bernard a very special friend.} 1. d4 e6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 b6 4. g3 Bb7 5.
Bg2 Be7 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Qc2 c5 8. d5 exd5 9. Ng5 h6  ({
Now I thought long and hard about playing} 9... Na6 $5 {
with the idea of playing after} 10. cxd5 Nb4 11. Qd2 Nfxd5 12. Nxf7 $6 Ne3 $3
13. fxe3 Bxg2 14. Nxd8 Bxh1 15. a3 (15. Qd1 Raxd8) 15... Bg2 16. Qxd7 Rf1+ 17.
Kd2 Rxd8 {winning, but Bernard has a huge database and can play 12.Nxd5 Bxg5
13.Qxg5 Qxg5 14.Bxg5 Bxd5 15.Bxd5 Nxd5 16.0-0-0 with quite a good plus. I was
sure he would find this. I also had vague memories of Korchnoi-Karpov 1974
which went 9...Nc6 10.Nxd5 g6 11.Qd2 Nxd5 12.Bxd5 Rb8 13.Nxh7 Re8 14.Qh6 Ne5
15.Ng5 Bxg5 16.Bxg5 Qxg5 17.Qxg5 Bxd5 18.0-0 Bxc4 19.f4 Black Resigns. Also 9..
.g6 10.cxd5 d6 runs into 11.h4! Therefore by a process of elimination I came
to...}) 10. Nxd5 Bxd5 11. cxd5 ({Also possible was} 11. Bxd5 Nc6 12. Bxc6 dxc6
13. Nf3 Qd7 14. O-O {when I planned to play14.. Qe6 which is about equal.})
11... Bd6 $5 {#I think this is new. 11...d6 was played in van der Stemen -
Karner Tallin 1987 and 11...hxg5!? between Balashov - Tiviakov St. Petersburg
1993 which continued 12.d6 Nc6 13.dxe7 Qxe7 14.Bxg5 d5 but I didn't fancy ny
two N's v 2 B's!} 12. Ne4 Nxe4 13. Bxe4 Re8 14. O-O Na6 {A look at the pawn
structure suggests the future course of the game. Black has passed pawn Qside
and White should push the e and f pawns aiming to obtain a winning attack with
e5. Whoever executes his plan first wins.} 15. a3 b5 16. Be3 $6 {I think this
is wrong. He should go 16.b3! He has to play b3 anyway. The move played just
clogs up the e file and delays White's strategic play of e4-e5 etc which never
gets going.} 16... Qf6 17. Rad1 Rac8 18. b3 c4 19. bxc4 Rxc4 20. Bh7+ Kh8 21.
Qb1 Rb8 22. Bd3 Rc7 23. Rd2 ({I was hoping for} 23. Bxb5 $2 Nc5 24. Bd4 Be5 25.
d6 Qxd6 26. Qa1 Bxd4 {when Black has a slight plus.}) 23... Nc5 24. Bf5 a6 25.
Rd4 {With this move White anounces his intention to attack Black's King!} 25...
Rd8 26. Rg4 Na4 27. Qd3 Be5 28. Rc1 $2 {An understandable mistake, the c3
square is very weak. The correct way to defend was by 28.Bd4 viz 28...d6 29.
Rf4! # 28...Nb2.} 28... Nb2 $1 {Now White has real problems with the f5 Bishop.
With 29.Qe4 Nc4 30.Rxc4 Rxc4 31.Qb1 Rc3 Black is winning. Also 29...Qxf5 wins.
Therefore White is forced into...} 29. Qb1 Nc4 30. Bd3 Nxe3 31. fxe3 Rxc1+ 32.
Qxc1 Qd6 33. Be4 a5 34. Bg2 f5 35. Rh4 {The only square for the Rook! I spent
some time trying to find a way to win this piece, but was happy to leave it
well offside!} 35... Rb8 36. Rh5 Qf8 37. Kf2 {
Strange, especially when 37.e4!? looks a far better try.} 37... b4 38. axb4
axb4 39. Qb1 g6 40. Rh4 b3 41. d6 b2 42. Bd5 Qxd6 43. Ba2 Ra8 {# With Bernards
last move 44.h3 came the offer if 44...Qd4!! White Resigns. The Correspondence
Chess card also had a photograph of Bernard from the 70's, kipper tie and
Gorilla hair style. I questioned his parentage and accepted his resignation.
This game will always remind me of all that is good in Correspondence Chess.}
44. h3 Qd4 0-1

